                otherExamples: "• <strong>Final Fantasy XVI</strong>: Final Fantasy XVI is a 2023 action RPG for PlayStation 5 featuring massive Eikon versus Eikon battles where titanic godlike beings clash in spectacular set-piece fights. When rival Dominants prime and transform, the game shifts into kaiju-scale warfare—Ifrit versus Phoenix at Phoenix Gate, flame against flame as brothers fight. Ifrit versus Garuda with wind and fire tearing across the sky. Ifrit versus Titan, a towering stone colossus hurling boulders as large as buildings while Ifrit dodges and burns. Phoenix versus Bahamut becomes an on-rails shooter with laser beams and fireballs. These battles have unique mechanics for each matchup: sometimes you're trading blows in melee, sometimes dodging environmental hazards, sometimes the camera pulls back to show two monsters grappling while mountains crumble around them. Each fight is desperate defense against overwhelming elemental force, standing your ground against a being of equal divine power trying to crush you. The Seven of Wands lives in those Eikon clashes: defending your position against overwhelming godlike opposition, standing ground when faced with forces of nature made flesh, fighting for survival against enemies of equal terrible power, holding your line while elemental chaos tears the world apart around you, the desperate battle where you're matched against impossible odds and must defend yourself through sheer determination and strength." +
                "• <strong>Kingdom Rush</strong>: Kingdom Rush is a 2011 tower defense game where you place Barracks, Archer Towers, Mage Towers, and Artillery along paths to stop waves of orcs, dark knights, demons, and other fantasy enemies from reaching the exit. Each tower can be upgraded and specialized—Barracks become Paladins or Barbarians, Archers become Rangers or Musketteers. You position Reinforcements to stall dangerous enemies at chokepoints, call down the Rain of Fire ability when lines are about to break, and desperately upgrade mid-wave as tougher enemies appear. The Seven of Wands lives in that escalating defense: you're outnumbered, each wave brings stronger threats, but you hold your position through strategic placement and refusing to let them break through." + 
                "• <strong>Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice</strong>: Sekiro is a 2019 action game where you play as Wolf, a shinobi surrounded by multiple attackers in Ashina Castle. Sword-wielding samurai, spear-throwers, and aggressive purple-robed warriors converge from all sides. You can't retreat; the terrain boxes you in. Success requires perfect deflection timing—sparks flying as you parry blade after blade—maintaining your posture while breaking theirs, striking when openings appear while tracking every threat. The Seven of Wands lives in Wolf's defensive stance: one against many, holding ground through skill and determination, refusing to yield despite overwhelming odds." + 
                "• <strong>Super Metroid</strong>: Super Metroid is a 1994 action-adventure game for SNES where defeating Mother Brain triggers Zebes's self-destruct sequence—you have exactly 3 minutes to escape before the entire planet explodes. Walls crumble around you, explosions tear through corridors, the path back to your ship is chaos. You run through collapsing rooms while the timer counts down relentlessly, fighting or evading Space Pirates still trying to kill you even as their world dies. Debris falls, platforms give way, environmental hazards activate. You're defending your right to survive while everything falls apart, standing your ground against the planet itself trying to destroy you, pushing forward through overwhelming destructive forces. If you choose, you can detour to save the Etecoons and Dachora—the small creatures who taught you wall-jumping and Shinespark earlier—breaking through additional obstacles to reach their room and free them before the explosion, adding extra risk to your desperate escape. The Seven of Wands lives in that escape sequence: fighting for survival against overwhelming odds, defending your position while the world crumbles, standing ground against forces trying to crush you, battling through mounting pressure and obstacles with time running out, choosing to protect others even when it endangers your own survival, holding your ground until the last possible second before the foundation collapses entirely." +
                "• <strong>Wild Arms 2</strong>: Wild Arms 2 is a 1999 JRPG where ARMS, a tiny counter-terrorism squad, defends the world of Filgaia against Odessa, a massive organization with superior numbers and resources. Ashley, Brad, and Lilka are constantly on the defensive, responding to threats across the planet, outmatched in every engagement. The Seven of Wands appears in that courageous defense: a small team holding the line because no one else will, fighting from moral high ground against enemies with every advantage except conviction. They refuse to yield, not through overwhelming power but through sheer determination.",
