                game: "Sonic the Hedgehog 2",
                keywords: "speed • swift action • rapid movement • momentum • messages • travel • things happening quickly • acceleration • air travel • fast progress",
                gameDescription: "Sonic the Hedgehog 2 is a 1992 platformer for Sega Genesis that perfected the franchise's speed-focused gameplay. You play as Sonic (with optional Tails following) blasting through zones like Emerald Hill, Chemical Plant, and Casino Night. The level design is built entirely around momentum: loop-de-loops that curl Sonic upside-down, ramps that launch him across vast gaps, corkscrews that spin the camera, dash panels that boost his velocity to maximum, and slopes where holding right makes Sonic accelerate into a blue blur. When Sonic hits his stride in stages like Hill Top Zone or Sky Chase Zone, the screen scrolls so fast you're reacting on pure instinct—jump, spin dash, bounce off springs, roll through tunnels. Collect rings while maintaining speed. The spin dash (new to Sonic 2) lets you charge up from a standstill and explode forward, building instant momentum. Boss fights are fast—Robotnik appears, you hit him eight times in rapid succession, he flees. The special stages put you in a half-pipe racing to collect rings before the stage ends, everything about speed and reflex. Sonic doesn't walk anywhere. His entire existence is acceleration, velocity, and the exhilaration of pure forward momentum. The Eight of Wands doesn't wait around, and neither does Sonic.",
