                gameDescription: "The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim is a 2011 open-world RPG where you play as the Dragonborn, a hero prophesied to save Tamriel from Alduin the World-Eater. The game gives you complete freedom to explore, loot, and collect—and that freedom becomes its own trap. Every dungeon is filled with items: iron daggers worth 10 gold, enchanted armor you might need later, crafting materials for potions you haven't made yet, dragon bones that weigh 15 pounds each, cheese wheels because why not. Your carrying capacity is limited, and when you exceed it, the screen flashes red: 'You are carrying too much to be able to run.' Suddenly you're shuffling forward at a fraction of normal speed, unable to sprint, unable to fast travel, stuck in a dungeon miles from the nearest merchant. Every step becomes a mental calculation: drop the ebony sword or the 47 potatoes? Abandon the valuable soul gems or the enchanted boots? The burden is entirely self-imposed—you chose to pick up everything—but it's very real. You're the savior of Skyrim, slayer of dragons, but you're crawling through corridors because you can't let go of iron daggers that might be worth something.",
                meaning: "You're carrying too much and it's weighing you down. Like an overencumbered Dragonborn barely able to walk, the Ten of Wands shows you've taken on more than you can reasonably handle. Responsibilities, obligations, projects, other people's problems—they've all accumulated into a crushing burden. You can't run anymore; you can barely move forward. This card isn't about noble sacrifice—it's about recognizing when you've overextended yourself. Something has to be dropped or delegated. Not everything in your inventory is essential, even if it seems valuable. Lighten your load before you collapse under the weight. Success shouldn't feel this heavy.",
                reflections: "• What responsibilities or obligations are weighing you down right now?\n• What can you delegate, drop, or let go of to lighten your load?\n• Are you holding onto things because they're valuable, or because you can't bear to let go?\n• What would it feel like to run freely again instead of trudging forward?",
                otherExamples: "• <strong>Death Stranding</strong>: Death Stranding is a 2019 action game where you play as Sam Porter Bridges, a courier tasked with reconnecting isolated cities across post-apocalyptic America by literally carrying cargo on his back. You stack packages high on Sam's frame—some strapped to his suit, others loaded precariously on floating carriers—until he's hunched under hundreds of pounds. Navigate treacherous terrain while maintaining balance using L2/R2 to shift weight, watching stamina drain with every step. Trip on a rock and cargo scatters everywhere; you must repack and continue. The Ten of Wands lives in bearing crushing burdens across hostile landscapes, struggling to maintain balance, accepting the weight because the mission requires it even as your body begs for rest." + 
                "• <strong>Final Fantasy II</strong>: Final Fantasy II is a 1988 RPG for NES that replaces traditional dialogue trees with a keyword system—you learn terms like \"Wild Rose,\" \"Mythril,\" \"Dreadnought,\" \"Ultima,\" then manually ask NPCs about specific keywords to unlock information and progress the story. Your inventory isn't just weapons and items—it's an ever-growing list of intelligence that you must carry and manage. Each town visit requires systematically asking everyone about every keyword to find the one person who knows the critical detail. You're carrying the rebellion's entire information network in your head: which keyword opens which conversation, who knows what about the Empire's movements, which term will trigger the next story beat. The system becomes burdensome—you're juggling dozens of keywords across multiple storylines, tracking which NPCs responded to which terms, managing the cognitive load of the rebellion's intelligence gathering. The Ten of Wands lives in that keyword inventory: carrying the heavy responsibility of the rebellion's information network, the burden of tracking who knows what and which terms matter where, managing essential but exhausting complexity, the weight of knowing that forgetting to ask the right person about the right keyword could stall the entire war effort, dutiful continuation despite the mounting cognitive load." +
                "• <strong>Pikmin 3</strong>: Pikmin 3 is a 2013 real-time strategy game where you command squads of plant-like Pikmin to gather resources. In the Tropical Wilds, your squad of 100 Pikmin struggles to carry the Armored Mawdad corpse back to the Onion. The creature is massive—it requires every single Pikmin working together, and they move agonizingly slow under its weight. You watch the day timer count down as they inch across the map, vulnerable to attacks because you've committed your entire workforce to this one burden. The Ten of Wands appears in watching your Pikmin strain under an enormous load, wondering if you've committed too many resources to a single task while the clock runs out." + 
                "• <strong>The Sims</strong>: The Sims is a 2000 life simulation game where you control virtual people through daily routines, managing every aspect of their lives. Your Sim wakes with every need bar flashing red—hunger critical, bladder about to burst, hygiene disgusting, energy depleted. The carpool honks outside. Bills arrived. The stove caught fire. A friend called angry. You frantically click between crises: send them to the bathroom and now they're starving, make food and now they're about to wet themselves. The Ten of Wands is that overwhelm: too many responsibilities demanding attention at once, trying to juggle every burden simultaneously, watching them crash because you're one person managing ten critical needs." +
                "• <strong>Space Invaders</strong>: Space Invaders is a 1978 arcade shooter where you control a lone laser cannon at the bottom of the screen defending against descending waves of alien invaders. The burden is relentless and ever-increasing: wave after wave marches down from above, never stopping, never giving you rest. As you destroy invaders, the remaining ones speed up—the closer you get to clearing a wave, the faster and harder it becomes. You're carrying the entire defense alone, exhausted, with no reinforcements coming. Your barriers erode under constant fire until you're completely exposed. The pressure mounts continuously as invaders descend closer to the bottom, the tempo accelerates, and you realize this burden is unsustainable—eventually you'll be overwhelmed. The Ten of Wands lives in that crushing weight: relentless responsibility with no relief, mounting pressure that accelerates as you progress, burden of defending everything solo, exhaustion from waves that never end, the realization that you can delay but never truly escape the overwhelming load bearing down on you.",
